M|references|source: wiki/concepts/Strategic Thinking/Systems Thinking.md
M|references|created: 2026-04-11
M|references|rv-by: 2026-07-11
M|references|Understand behavior by examining the whole system, not isolated parts. System behavior emerges from the interactions between components, not from the components themselves.
M|references|| Concept | Definition | Example |
M|references||---------|-----------|---------|
M|references|| Feedback loops | Output feeds back as input, amplifying or dampening | Team velocity drops, so management adds process, which drops velocity further |
M|references|| Emergence | System behavior not predictable from individual parts | Microservices that each work fine but create cascading failures together |
M|references|| Delays | Effects lag behind causes | tec debt accrues silently, then explodes during a critical feature push |
M|references|| Leverage points | Small changes with outsized impact | Fixing a shared library bug vs patching each consumer |
M|references|| Mental models | Assumptions that shape how we interpret the system | "More engineers = faster delivery" (ignoring Brooks's Law) |
M|references|Use this model during **Challenge** (Steps 5-6) to identify second-order effects and feedback loops.
M|references|When evaluating any dec:
M|references|1. What feedback loops does this dec create or break?
M|references|2. What are the second-order effects? Third-order?
M|references|3. Where are the delays between action and consequence?
M|references|4. What leverage points exist? Are we acting on them or on symptoms?
M|references|5. What mental models are we assuming that might be wrong?
M|references|| Signal | Risk |
M|references||--------|------|
M|references|| "This only affects component X" | Ignoring system interconnections |
M|references|| "We'll see results immediately" | Ignoring delays in the system |
M|references|| "More resources will fix it" | Linear thinking in a nonlinear system |
M|references|| "We fixed the symptom" | Root cause unaddressed, will resurface |
M|references|| Optimizing one metric aggressively | Goodhart's Law: metric becomes the target, not the goal |
M|references|For each proposed dec, trace effects through at least two levels:
M|references|```
M|references|dec: [proposed action]
M|references|-> First-order: [immediate, intended effect]
M|references|-> Second-order: [downstream consequence]
M|references|-> Third-order: [further ripple effect]
M|references|```
M|references|- "What if this fix creates a worse problem elsewhere in the system?"
M|references|- "What feedback loop are we accidentally creating?"
M|references|- "Are we treating the symptom or the cause?"
M|references|- "What will this look like in 6 months when delays manifest?"
M|references|- Fixing a symptom while the root cause generates new symptoms
M|references|- Creating reinforcing feedback loops that accelerate problems
M|references|- Ignoring delays and declaring success before consequences arrive
M|references|- Optimizing a subsystem at the expense of the whole system
M|references|- Missing leverage points and applying effort where impact is lowest
M|references|Before accepting a dec as VERIFIED:
M|references|- [ ] System boundaries defined (what is inside/outside scope)
M|references|- [ ] Feedback loops identified (reinforcing and balancing)
M|references|- [ ] Second-order effects traced for at least 2 levels
M|references|- [ ] Delays between action and effect estimated
M|references|- [ ] Leverage points identified and targeted
M|references|- [ ] Mental model assumptions stated explicitly
M|references|- Gall's Law: complex systems evolve from simple ones
M|references|- Chesterton's Fence: understand the system before changing it
M|references|- Survivorship Bias: examine the full system, not just visible outputs